BusinessAnalysis & Features Mastercard's Ann Cairns: From ‘one of the lads’ on a North Sea rig to a City leading lady

As she constantly struggles to replace cash in the economy, the credit card boss believes London’s financial services are on the up 

Friday 31 May 2013 09:57 BST







Click to followThe Evening Standard














 



As the first woman to work offshore on UK oil rigs, the start of Ann Cairns’ career wasn’t all that glamorous. “There were no women’s loos, and no locks on the doors either, so I had to sit with my feet on the door so no one came in,” she remembers of her spell in her twenties working as British Gas’s only woman in the southern North Sea basin. “I had long blonde hair when I started, but I had that cut off very quickly. I was definitely one of the lads.” She still sports a blonde pixie haircut, but her current job, dashing around the world as the number two in charge of MasterCard, has a bit more glamour. Better lavatories, too. As boss of the payments group’s international business, Cairns checks out operations in Asia, South America and Europe, all the regions outside the US which now account for 60% of the payments group’s revenues. There’s a spot of Champions League football to fit in (MasterCard sponsors it, and she hosted suits at Wembley last week) and some theatre too (last month’s Olivier Awards at the Royal Opera House were also backed by MasterCard).But it all started on the rigs. Cairns — a softly spoken Geordie — nabbed the job after British Gas phoned up her tutors at Newcastle University, looking for a statistician. “And I thought all the interesting stuff happened offshore, so phoned up the bloke who managed it and talked my way into an interview.” She worked her way up to managing a team of 50 engineers, ultimately spending three years commuting between the North Sea and Irish Sea and her husband in south London. That experience was followed by a move into banking, including six years at ABN Amro — before its dalliance with Royal Bank of Scotland — and 15 years at Citigroup, ultimately running its transaction banking. It was there that Cairns first combined her career with parenthood, giving birth to her daughter at 37. “It never affected my career,” she says. “In fact, I actually got promoted while on maternity leave. I was recovering from a caesarean when my boss phoned and said ‘when are you coming back? I need you’. He asked me to run Citi’s product development in Europe, which I thought was a great vote  of confidence.”Cairns’ own experience means she is “disappointed” that the gender balance in British business is still so skewed towards men. She admits her own situation was helped by the fact that her husband is a teacher, so when her family moved around the world for Cairns’ work (including two spells in the US and one in Holland at ABN Amro), “he always got a job in whatever country we were in, at the school [daughter] Sophie was attending. That made it much easier for me, but in general I think things aren’t improving as fast as they should be for women at work here.” There’s still a dearth of offers for boardroom seats for women, Cairns says, which means she isn’t so anti-quotas as other high-flying female finance executives such as Newton Asset Management’s chief executive Helena Morrissey. “It would be a shame if we had to introduce quotas here — you want to feel you’ve got to your position on your own merits — but in Britain there isn’t a great track record,” says Cairns, who is 56. “I get many more calls with offers from European boards, places like Holland, and France, because they have targets and quotas.”She believes that headhunters have the biggest role to play: “They should give firms a long and full slate of candidates of both sexes, rather than rely on their existing networks and phoning up the same people time and time again, which still happens.” There’s certainly a “slate” of women at MasterCard: joining Cairns at the top is finance director Martina Hund-Mejean while the UK boss is Marion King, who joined from payments group VocaLink. But running MasterCard’s international business hasn’t been Cairns’ first high-profile role. She was working as head of financial industry advisory in Europe at restructuring giant Alvarez & Marsal in 2008 when Lehman Brothers collapsed. “I had only been there a few weeks and was sitting in my office in Canary Wharf and saw everyone walking out of the building with their boxes,” she says. “Then a couple of days later, I got a call from Bryan Marsal, one of the founders of Alvaraz, telling me he had taken over running Lehman’s Chapter 11, and I was in charge of the work in Europe, winding up Lehman Brothers Holdings International. We had 200,000 complex swaps here in London, and right until the end the people running Lehman didn’t expect it to fail. They thought a deal would be done.” The work caught MasterCard’s eye though, and Cairns now says her job is to “constantly fight to replace cash in the economy”. Some 85% of the world’s financial transactions are still cash and paper. “And there’s a misconception that cash is free. It’s not. It costs 0.5% to 1.5% of a country’s GDP to have cash circulating around, with leakage, reconciling funds, and fraud. If  you apply that 1% average to the British economy, then you would save £20 billion by taking cash out.”But even as things stand, MasterCard — which makes about 1p from a £10 transaction from a consumer doing some shopping — isn’t doing too badly. Pre-tax profit rose 12% in the first quarter of the year to $766 million (£508 million). The company was listed in New York in 2006 at $39, and the shares are now worth about $577.But it’s still the world’s number two payment provider, behind Visa — hence Cairns’ weekly travel. “We’re constantly looking at partnering up and buying companies to extend our reach,”  she says. Two UK deals in the past few years — the acquisition of  e-commerce payment business Datacash and a pre-pay card business from Travelex - totted up to $1 billion.Are more UK acquisitions on the horizon? Cairns looks coy: “I couldn’t say if there were — prices would shoot up.” But the future of financial services here is, she reckons, as bright as her bus-red blazer. “It  is very bad for us to have a dislike of such a core part of this country,  and I hope the batterings are over,” she says. “We have some good  people in charge of our banks  now, and the regulatory regime is coming together. “I really do think London’s financial services are on the up.”LIFE AND TIMESCV MILESTONESFirst jobs Statistician for British Gas, then 15 years in senior operational positions at Citigroup 2005 Chief executive, transaction banking at ABN Amro2008 Head of financial services in Europe at Alvarez & Marsal, winding up Lehman Brothers Holdings Intnl2011 President of international markets, MasterCardPERSONAL LIFEMarried to a teacher, daughter studying English at university. Loves sailing and owns a boat in Palma, Spain: “You can completely switch off when you’re sailing”.BEST ADVICE I'VE RECEIVED“Always instinctively do the right thing and be clear and transparent about your decisions — that’s the best protection when you are dealing with a crisis and have incomplete information,” from Bryan Marsal, who led the winding-up of Lehman Brothers at Alvarez & Marsal. 

